# Module Documentation Protocol

After **every** module creation or modification, update the corresponding file in `/docs/modules/`.

## Folder Structure

Place each doc in the correct subfolder:

| Subfolder | What goes here |
|-----------|---------------|
| `docs/modules/api/` | Next.js API route handlers (`src/app/api/**`) |
| `docs/modules/database/` | DB connection, schema, seed (`src/lib/db/**`) |
| `docs/modules/components/` | React UI components (`src/components/**`) |
| `docs/modules/hooks/` | Custom hooks and context providers (`src/hooks/**`) |
| `docs/modules/pages/` | Next.js page files (`src/app/**/page.tsx`) |

## Rules

- **File naming:** `[module-name].md` (kebab-case, matching the source file name)
- **One file per module:** each source file or logical feature gets its own `.md`
- **Update on every change:** if you modify a module, update its doc in the same task before closing

## Required Content Schema

Each doc must contain these sections **in this order**:

```
## Plain English
A jargon-free, 2–4 sentence explanation that anyone (non-developer) can understand.
Describe what the module does, why it exists, and when it runs — no technical terms.

## Purpose
Technical summary of what the module does and why it exists.

## Exported Functions / Components
List each export with its signature and a one-line description.

## Dependencies
Internal (`@/`) and external (`npm`) imports this module relies on.

## State & Side Effects
Any React state, context, reducers, or external side effects (DB writes, fetch calls).

## How It Works
Step-by-step explanation of the module's internal logic flow.
```

## Verification

Before concluding any task that touches source files, confirm:
- The corresponding doc exists in the correct subfolder
- The **Plain English** section is present and written in simple, clear language
- The doc reflects the current state of the file (not a previous version)
